Here’s how I overcame my fear of failure…⁣
⁣
1. Redefining failure: I was always worried about doing something wrong, not meeting expectations, or looking stupid (fear of failure). Every time I thought of doing something new it brought me back to those thoughts and I realized I was already blocking myself and dreading anything new before even starting it. I was already failing in my mind before giving myself the opportunity to get started. It’s so interesting how powerful our mind is.⁣ The same way you’re creating negative outcomes in your mind (fear) you can choose to create positive ones (faith). They are both made up scenarios in your mind, so why not create the positive story? 
⁣
2. Created a list of my fears: It’s like writing a list of your problems, there is always a solution. When you focus on the good, the good gets better. When you focus on the bad, the bad gets worse. ⁣
⁣
3. Focus on learning: Life doesn’t always go as planned, expect the unexpected. We all learn in life from experiences. Tell me one lesson you’ve ever learned from a PERFECT day? You probably cannot. Life’s greatest lessons come from tough days. ⁣
⁣
✨Remember it’s when you feel comfortable that you should be fearful, because it’s a sign that you’re not stepping far enough out of your comfort zone to take steps that will help you rise & thrive. ✨

Hear me out…⁣
⁣
There are millions of Realtors but that doesn’t stop anyone from becoming one. There are millions of Teachers but that doesn’t stop anyone either. ⁣The word “saturation” is really a mindset. Think about this…how many Starbucks and Target Stores are in your city? 
⁣
I’ve never been the one to let anyone or anything stop me from doing what I want to do because of who may be doing it. I knew I wanted more than I had and I wasn’t going to achieve it at my job. Things like flexibility, working from home, making over $100K, having unlimited PTO…to name a few. 
⁣
I started Direct Sales scared, with no experience, zero knowledge of social media (not tech savvy at all) and to be 100% honest without any expectations. All I wanted at first was to simply make $200 a month. I was very shy when I started and felt silly doing something outside of my Corporate job, but I went for it either way. ⁣Anything new will always be “scary” at first, that means you’re growing and doing something new. 
⁣
3 years later I have been able to retire from the Corporate world, have the flexibility to work remote or anywhere from my phone, drive a paid for luxury car and have traveled over 8 times fully paid for by my company. ⁣
⁣
What would your life look like if you let go of your limiting beliefs? ⁣Have you taken the time to really look at the opportunities that are around you? 
⁣
Dm me “INFO” let’s chat. ⁣

3 simple things I would never do to my hair…

Oiling my hair & scalp has been a game changer. It helped set my scalp into the healthiest environment for my hair to heal & strengthen from the inside out. 

Shampoo with silicones is a BIG, no no! I can’t believe I did this for so long (until 4 years ago to be exact). This clogs the pores in your scalp and prevents you from stimulating new growth. 

Washing everyday! Yup! You heard it here first. This causes unnecessary dryness and damage. If you’re washing daily due to your scalp feeling oily - you can actually be causing an overproduction or if you’re washing due to your hair feeling dry - you could also be causing unnecessary dryness simply by over washing. 

Washing 2-3 x a week at most with hair specific products is key!

* itchiness 
* dryness 
* dandruff
* extreme oiliness 
* hair fall out

Busting common hair myths!

Myth #1: Cutting Your Hair More Frequently Encourages Growth

On average, hair grows about a quarter of an inch each month, and no amount of regular trimming can make it grow any faster. In fact, given that hair growth is entirely dependent on the hair follicle and root, it makes absolutely no sense to think that trimming the ends of the hair would have any effect on its growth patterns. 

Yes, it’s always great to get rid of dead ends & even out the hair but cutting it so often is NOT going to make your hair grow.
